__data__.text: The University of Washington Climate Impacts Group published a climate change impacts assessment report for Washington State in 2013.
The Economic Impacts of Climate Change in Washington State report was published in 2007.
The 2007 report summarized the impacts of climate change on forest fires, public health, agriculture, municipal water supply, sea level rise, and fisheries in Washington State.
The predictions in the 2007 report were based primarily on temperature and precipitation models for climate change.
The expected warming is 0.5 °F (0.2 °C) every ten years.
Total annual precipitation is not expected to change significantly.
The increase in temperatures will result in a more minimal snowpack leading to more rain.

Visible physical impacts on the environment within Washington State include glacier reduction, declining snowpack, earlier spring runoff, an increase in large wildfires, and rising sea levels which affect the Puget Sound area.
The major impacts of climate change in Washington State (2007) include an increase in carbon dioxide (CO2) levels and an increase in temperatures.
The estimated temperature increase is 2 °F (1.1 °C) by 2020 and up to 3 °F (1.7 °C) by 2040.
Sea level rise of about 3 inches to 3 feet (0.91 m) by 2100 is expected.
There will be no change in volume of precipitation.
Less snowpack will result in a time change of water flow volumes into freshwater systems.
Greater winter river volume, and less volume during summer's driest months, generally from July through October, will occur.
These changes will result in both economic and ecological repercussions, most notably found in hydrological power output, municipal water supply and migration of fish.
Climate change impacts are visible and the economic effects are becoming apparent in Washington State.
The costs of climate change will grow as temperatures and sea levels rise in Washington State.
Climate change will provide economic opportunities in Washington State.

North Cascades National Park has experienced a significant loss of glaciers since 1959, with an estimated 80% reduction in ice.
Some streams in North Cascades National Park, such as Thunder Creek, get about half of their late-summer flow from glaciers.
The receding glaciers in Thunder Creek have reduced summer streams by 31%.
Between 1913 and 1994, Mount Rainier National Park's glaciers lost 21% of their area.
Glacier retreat has been recorded for Blue Glacier and others in Olympic National Park.
Higher temperatures may cause trees to take over the meadows in Paradise Valley, preventing wildflowers from growing.
Washington State has 43,000,000 acres of forestland, which support various economic activities like timber production and wildlife habitat protection.
In 2002, total employment in lumber, wood products, pulp, and paper in Washington State was 43,700.
Timber collected on public land accounts for 16% of the current output from the lumber industry in Washington State.
Climate change may impact the economic contribution of Washington's forests both directly and indirectly through various factors like tree growth rates, pest infestations, and fire damage.
Climate change can affect tree growth by altering temperature levels, soil moisture, and atmospheric CO2 concentrations.
A study in El Dorado County, California, suggests a reduction of timber yields by 18-31% by the end of the 21st century due to increased summer temperatures.
Climate change may introduce new pests to Washington's forests, posing downside risks, while the loss of existing pests may have little impact.
Washington State relies on hydropower for 72% of its power, with $4.3 billion in hydropower sales in 2003.
Climate change will negatively affect both the supply and demand of electricity in Washington State.

Summer demand for electricity may increase due to the need for air conditioning.
Washington State relies on hydropower for 66% of its electricity generation.
Changes in peak snowpack melt and stream flows could affect the availability of electricity in Washington State.
Peak stream flows in Washington State occur in the summer.
Increased temperatures may cause snowpack to melt earlier, shifting peak stream flow to late winter and early spring, and decreasing summer stream flow.
This shift in peak stream flow could result in increased availability of electricity in early spring, when demand is dampened, and decreased availability in the summer, when demand may be highest.

The Northwest Power and Conservation Council predicts that the economic impact of climate change in Washington could result in a deficit of $169 million in power sales by 2020 and $730 million by 2040.
Hydropower is more susceptible to climate change impacts than other sources of electricity.
Washington residents pay lower costs for electricity than the national average.
Increased temperatures in the summer months will alter the selling of electricity to other states and cause the state to lose money.
Seattle's municipal water systems may hit capacity in 2050.
Experts predict shorter winters and longer summers, which could lead to winter flooding and more severe summer droughts.
A 2005 University of Washington study states that the city of Seattle could see a 14% drop in water supply by 2040.
The Seattle Public Utilities estimates that it will be able to maintain 171 million US gallons (650,000 m3) per day production for the next 50 years.
The water demand is estimated to maintain itself at 130 million US gallons (490,000 m3) per day.
However, these numbers fail to take into account the effects of climate change.
It is predicted that by 2040 the water levels will actually decrease to 147 million US gallons (560,000 m3) per day.

Winter and early spring produce more water than late spring flows.
A lack of water will be problematic for both humans and the region's wildlife.
The municipal water supply problem will affect different regions differently.
Everett has a population of 100,000 and the Sultan river provides it with a vast amount of water.
Global warming will have a minimal effect on the supply of water to Everett.
The Seattle region gets the bulk of its water from the Cedar River and Tolt River watersheds.
New water sources must be found as water levels decrease in the Cedar River and Tolt River watersheds.
The Cascade Water Alliance proposed using Lake Tapps as a new source of drinkable water.
The Lake Tapps project is projected to cost $450 million and take decades to complete.
Reservoirs hold the early spring melt of snow for summer months.
Reservoirs must be made larger to hold more of the early spring runoff.
This reservoir expansion will cost millions, if not billions, of dollars to taxpayers.
By 2040, snowpack levels that used to dip to a dangerously low level every 50 years will do so every 5 years.
No matter the size of the reservoir, if there is not enough water to fill them then they will be of little help.
An alternative to curtailing water usage would be to increase the price consumers pay for water.
Washington State is one of the nine contiguous states that has mountainous glaciers.
These glaciers produce 30 billion cubic feet (850,000,000 m3) of water every year.
Glaciers in the Olympic Range and the Northern Cascades are losing their size rapidly.
The Southern Cascade Glacier in Darington has lost two-thirds of its volume.
Glaciers have, on average, decreased by 31 feet (9.4 m) and between 18 and 32% of their volume of water.

Snow dominant regions have their highest water flow several months after their highest snowfall.
The increase in temperature causes snow dominant regions to act more like transition regions.
Transition regions have two peak flows, one in the spring due to snowmelt, and the other in the winter due to water falling as rain, not snow.
Transition regions now act like rain regions which have their high points in river flows right after it rains.
Agriculture is probably responsive to climate variability and weather extremes, such as droughts, floods, and severe storms.
Human activity has already changed atmospheric characteristics such as temperature, rainfall, levels of carbon dioxide (CO2) and ground level ozone.
The scientific community expects such trends to continue.
Warmer climate may give positive effects on food production.
The increased potential for weather extremes will pose challenges for farmers.
Water supply and soil moisture could make it less feasible to continue crop production in certain areas.

The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC, 2007) concluded that increased frequency of heat stress, droughts and floods negatively affect crop yields and livestock beyond the impacts of mean climate change.
Climate variability and change also modify the risks of fires, pest and pathogen outbreak, negatively affecting food, fiber, and forestry.

Several factors directly connect climate change and agricultural productivity, including change in precipitation amount and patterns, rising atmospheric concentrations of CO2, and pollution levels such as ground level ozone.
Change in climatic variability and extreme events also impact agriculture.
Most agricultural impact studies have considered the effects of one or two aspects of climate change on a particular farming activity.
Few studies have considered the full set of anticipated shifts and their impact on agricultural production across the country.
The ways in which climate changes in Washington will affect agriculture are largely unknown.
One benefit which climate change may potentially have on agriculture is the possibility of longer growing seasons.
Some of the negative effects of climate change on agriculture include reduced water supply and higher demand for water.

The Columbia River Gorge is starting to adapt to warmer temperatures by having a third generation yearly.
Increased numbers of hot days over 100 °F are expected to cause increased levels of heat-related illness.
The agricultural workers population is especially vulnerable to heat-related illness.
Simple tools developed to forecast the impacts of El Niño on agriculture irrigation can also be used to estimate the impacts of water shortages during climate change.
Studies are focusing on the water availability to the 370,000 acres of orchards, vineyards, and food crops within the Yakima River Valley.
The effects of a climate change in the region are being exploited in these studies.
Irrigation draws water from only five reservoirs and snowpack from the Cascades.
Early snowfall and a premature diminish are causing a decrease in irrigation water supply.
A 20-40% decrease in irrigation water supply is predicted in a year at mid-century.
The loss to agriculture in the Yakima River Valley would be $92 million for a 2 °C increase and $163 million for a 4 °C increase.
The amount of rainfall may not change in this region, but the snowpack will due to rising temperatures.
The reduction of snowpack will lower the availability of water during critical growing seasons.
Changes in temperature and precipitation caused by climate change means risk management options will take a more permanent form when addressing changes in crops, cultivators, and adding storage.
Dairy production in Washington state will be negatively affected by a significant rise in global temperatures.
There were 560 dairy farms in Washington state at the end of 2004.
By 2075, milk production in the Yakima River Valley will drastically decrease during the summer months.
The worst effects of climate change will be a decrease in daily milk production from 27 kg to 20 kg in the month of August.
Whatcom County dairy farms are predicted to be less affected by climate change than Yakima Valley.

Chardonnay grapes in Western Washington mature well at 14-16 °C.
Merlot grapes produced in Eastern Washington do best at 16-19 °C.
A shift in vineyard concentration to coastal regions would result in a change in local land value and use, production, revenue, and employment due to an increase in average temperature.
Scientists are concerned about the impact of extreme weather caused by global climate change on vineyards, especially those grown east of the Cascade Range.
Eastern Washington produces a significant amount of wheat.
Some models of daily temperature do not account for the topography in eastern Washington, resulting in inaccurate temperature predictions.
Topography and temperature affect the yield of wheat.
A new system called the Regional Climate Model (RCM) considers topographical data, resulting in a more accurate temperature estimate.
A recent study found that winter wheat productions were highest in areas with ample rainfall, temperate conditions, and at elevations between 1000 and 1500 meters.
Both non-irrigated and irrigated harvests have increased with global warming, allowing for increased production at higher elevations.
Harvests also improved with the presence of higher levels of carbon dioxide.
Cranberry production in Washington makes up a moderate amount (less than a tenth of a percent) of agricultural revenue for the state.
Higher winter temperatures due to climate change could result in considerable losses in revenue for cranberry production in Washington.
Washington is the fifth largest supplier of cranberries in the U.S., producing 3% of total U.S. production.
There are three growing regions for cranberries in Washington, including Whatcom County, Grays Harbor County, and Pacific County.
The fishing industry in Washington depends heavily on the Pacific Ocean, Puget Sound, the Columbia River, and many other rivers.
The UNEP reported that three quarters of the world's key fishing grounds are at risk of being seriously impacted by rising temperatures.

The snowpack captures winter precipitation at higher altitudes. It acts as a bank, slowly releasing water during dryer months.
Decrease in snowpack levels will lead to earlier peak flows in area streams and rivers.
Decrease in snowpack levels will increase flooding.
Decrease in snowpack levels will lead to loss of irrigation and drinking water.
Decrease in snowpack levels will affect threatened salmon runs.
Climate change can lead to loss of habitat and native species.
Warmer temperatures allow the northern movement of invasive species.
The Swollen Bladderwort is an invasive, free-floating carnivorous plant.
The Swollen Bladderwort can be easily spread by waterfowl.
The Swollen Bladderwort has adapted to reproduce in multiple ways.
Uncontrolled spread of the Swollen Bladderwort reduces the water's oxygen content.
Uncontrolled spread of the Swollen Bladderwort increases fish mortality rates.
Uncontrolled spread of the Swollen Bladderwort poses a danger to boats.
Increased temperature and loss of snowpack increase mortality among juvenile salmon.
This is particularly true in the Snohomish River Basin and hydrologically similar watersheds.
Increases in reservoirs and flood-control structures can mitigate peak-flow effects.
However, increased loss of habitat and reduced escapement from increasing temperatures significantly impact the state's overall commercial, recreational and tribal fisheries.
Seattle is home to the Alaskan fish fleet.
Any current change in the amount of fishing allowed negatively affects Seattle's economy.
Commercial fisheries are already characterized by full utilization of resources, large overcapacity, and conflicts among fishers.
Climate change adds a further argument for developing effective and flexible fisheries management systems in an ecosystem context.

The Northwest Emergency Assistance Plan provided $25 million in economic aid.
$13.6 million of the $25 million was allocated to the State of Washington.
The funds supported habitat restoration, data collection, and salmon license buyback programs.
The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) provided an additional $10 million in disaster unemployment assistance.

The Small Business Administration made low-interest loans and debt-restructuring available.
The potential costs of supporting commercial salmon fisheries may continue to increase due to global warming.
Government-sponsored buyback programs may become more expensive as global warming impacts commercial salmon fisheries.
Buybacks take the form of Vessel Buyback Programs and License Retirement Programs.
The average cost of a license or vessel purchased in these plans is $10,000 for salmon and small vessel fleets.
The cost of a factory trawler purchased in these plans can rise as high as $10 million.
Nationally, these programs have totaled $160 million since 1976.
Lake Washington holds the largest urban sport salmon fishery in the United States.
The temperature of Lake Washington's upper layers has risen more than 2.5 °F (1.388 °C) in the past 40 years.
The overall water temperature in Lake Washington has increased a full degree Fahrenheit.
Warmer temperatures in Lake Washington have negatively impacted local salmon runs.
Zooplankton populations, such as Daphnia, have declined in Lake Washington due to warmer temperatures.
Increased temperatures have delayed fall turnover and maintained stratification nearly 4 weeks longer than in previous years.
Earlier stratification has resulted in earlier algal blooms, which are necessary food for zooplankton.

Increases in water temperatures could affect the food for fish in rivers, lakes, Puget Sound, and coastal ocean regions.
Fishing is a significant business in the Pacific Northwest, and many local economies depend on fishing.
The allocation of the salmon run is a contentious issue, with local Native American tribes, commercial fishermen, and sport fishermen vying for a share.
Native American tribes have a treaty-guaranteed maximum of 50% of the total run before commercial and sport fishers take their share.
Sport fishermen spend more money per fish caught and drive the economy through the Spending multiplier throughout the local economy.
During 2007, commercial fishermen caught 43% and sport fishermen caught 57% of the total fish.

The Washington Department of Health spends $246,000 per year on surveillance for the West Nile virus and epidemiological follow-up and testing on suspected human cases.

Global warming has a direct effect on respiratory illnesses.

In 1992, the United States Congress provided for increased emphasis on coastal non-point pollution.
The state of Washington is developing a Coastal Non-point Pollution Management plan as part of the national Coastal Zone Management (CZM) program.
Washington participates in the federal Coastal and Estuarine Land Conservation Program (CELCP).
The CELCP aims to protect critical coastal and estuarine areas with significant conservation, recreational, ecological, historical, or aesthetic values, which are threatened by conversion.
Dedicated grant funds for the CELCP have not been authorized by the U.S. Congress.
A state plan has been drafted in Washington to ensure eligibility for future participation in the CELCP.
Research is being conducted on the effects on coastal boundaries in Oregon and California.
Washington's economy is susceptible to the impacts of climate change in the mountains due to the large ski industry.
Climate change will result in more rain and less snow across mountainous regions in Washington.
Earlier melting of Washington's snowpack will negatively affect slope conditions and water supply.
The breakdown of the snowpack occurs in early spring, leaving summer months dry and ending winter sports much earlier than before.
Over 40% of winter recreation in the past 10 years took place at lower elevation ski areas.
Snoqualmie Summit, Mt. Baker, and Mt. Spokane ski areas are most likely to be affected by climate change.
The Summit at Snoqualmie experienced "warm winters" in 27% of the years from 1971 to 2000.
The Summit at Snoqualmie may experience over 50% "warm winters" by 2040.
Washington's ski resorts contribute greatly to the state's economy.
There was an average of 1.65 million visits per year to Washington's ski areas over the last decade.
Annual revenue from Washington's ski areas ranges from $50–$150 million for ski passes, tickets, and rentals.
Protecting shorelines from sea level rise (SLR) can be done by building seawalls or pumping sand onto beaches to prevent erosion.
Managing river flow to redirect increased water levels is another method to control SLR.
The cost to protect shorelines from SLR is difficult to calculate due to variability in land quality and development.
An estimate of the potential national cost to protect land from a one-meter rise in SLR, excluding future value, is $270-475 billion.
Washington State has over 3,000 miles of shoreline and is vulnerable to climate-related shoreline changes due to SLR.
The impact of SLR on Washington State will depend on the amount of rise, estimated to be between 3 inches and over 40 inches within the next 100 years.
A two-foot rise in SLR will affect 44,429 Washington residences and cover an area of 56 square miles.
Agricultural areas such as Willapa Bay and the Skagit River Delta including Fir Island will be the first to be impacted by rising tides due to SLR.
The Cascade Peninsula is rising in step with the rising oceans, but other areas of the coastline are vulnerable to the rising waters.
The Puget Sound region is vulnerable to SLR as it is subsiding at a rate of around 24 mm a decade.
Higher water levels and more catastrophic waves will cause higher rates of damage to the coast line due to SLR.
The changing sea levels will decrease tidal flats, affecting the population of shellfish and other coastal animals.
The economic effects of such land changes would be the decrease in shellfish supply and a decrease in land value as marshes grow.
Waterfront property generates much of the residential tax base for coastal communities.

The increase in temperature is expected to cause sea levels to rise due to ocean warming and melting ice caps and glaciers.

Commercial and recreational activities in coastal areas, such as shipping terminals, marinas, docks, and recreational facilities, will be affected by flooding.
Ecological impacts due to climate change are expected to be significant, both directly and indirectly.
Washington's temperature is expected to increase by 0.1 - 0.6 °C (0.2-1.0 °F) per decade.
Wildfires will become more frequent and devastating due to climate change.
Climate change will cause problems for wildlife, including changes in distribution and temporal mismatching of phenological events.
Statewide assessments will determine which species and habitats to preserve, but they may not provide protection to the same species in the future due to ecosystem variation.
Wildlife populations are expected to become extinct due to climate change-induced ecosystem shifts.
Changes in plant wildlife due to climate change have already been observed.
Plants have become more efficient in water use due to greater atmospheric carbon dioxide concentration, potentially resulting in changes in community composition and vegetation types.
Tree lines have been observed advancing further north and upward vertically due to increasing temperatures.
There is little research on climate change's effects on non-vascular plants, but current findings suggest that most lower elevation non-vascular plant communities will increase in biodiversity.
Higher elevation non-vascular plants are expected to suffer from reductions of growth and range due to the upwardly invading tree line.
Changes in species distribution and habitats are likely to be observed due to reductions of snowpack and summer water availability.
Plants may experience a reduction in habitat due to the upwardly invading tree line.

This expansion will result in the extinction or vast reduction of many grassland and sagebrush steppe communities.
Changes in growing season and temperatures will result in earlier leafing-out and/or flowering of many species.
These changes may cause temporal mismatches between herbivores and availability of key food staples.
Temporal mismatches may also be seen in parasite/host and pollinator/plant relationships.
Many species have been observed to migrate northward at an average of 6 km per decade over the past century.
An expected increase in temperatures may cause even more range shifts and reordering of ecological communities.
The greatest impacts upon invertebrate land animals will be seen in the areas of northward and vertical migration and phenological changes.
Changes in the distribution of insects active year-round have already been observed.

Temporal mismatching of species' biological events may cause more complicated problems.
The timing of butterfly hatching and the flowering of their host plants may drift apart, especially in years of drought or excessive snowpack.
This drift may result in the complete crash or extinction of many species or populations.
The greatest ecological impact concerning invertebrates as a result of climate change will likely be seen in the destruction caused by insects whose populations expand in both range and lifespan.

Mammals seem to be resilient to the effects of climate change.
There are connections between fecundity, juvenile survival, and winter temperatures in mammals.
Distribution shifts northward and upward in elevation can be expected for mammals due to climate change.
Amphibians are at risk of being negatively affected by climate change.
The dependence on water regimes and specific microhabitats makes amphibians vulnerable to climate change.
Limited dispersal abilities of amphibians make it difficult for them to adapt to climate change.

Habitat modification caused by wildfires, fire changes, and changes in sea water levels and quality indirectly affects amphibians.
Direct consequences associated with rising temperatures also impact amphibians.
Phenological challenges are more prominent in amphibians than in other vertebrates.
Calling and breeding phenology in spring has advanced in amphibians.
Six different frog species in New York State have experienced a 10- to 13-day advancement in callings associated with 1 °C to 2.3 °C rises in temperature during breeding months.
Studies in England have shown an advancement of amphibian breeding by 2 to 7 weeks over a 17-year time period.

In 2011, the Washington State Department of Ecology released the interim recommendations of a multi-stakeholder collaboration on preparing Washington's natural systems for the impacts of climate change.
The recommendations include goals and strategies for building the capacity of Washington's species, habitats, and ecosystems to adapt to the effects of climate change.
Greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions are due to anthropogenic GHG concentrations.
Human activities, including burning fossil fuels, waste, and wood products, cause CO2 emissions.
CO2 is the least common type of GHG, while water vapor is the most common.
Methane is emitted during coal, natural gas, or oil production.
Other sources of methane include agricultural livestock and decaying organic matter.
Nitrous oxide is emitted through industrial and agricultural activities.
Many industrial companies have switched from burning coal and petroleum fuel to natural gas.
More toxic pollutants such as hydrofluorocarbons and sulfur hexafluoride, are emitted in smaller rates and are known as High Global Warming Potential Gases.
The Washington State Department of Ecology regularly publishes GHG inventories.
The Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) helps forward the process by providing the state with inventory guidance and technical assistance.
These inventories provide the state with useful information about emissions.
From these inventories, policies will be implemented and added to the State Climate Change Action Plan.

Seattle's Climate Action Plan aims to reduce greenhouse gases (GHG) by approximately 680,000 tons per year.

The plan includes reducing Seattle's dependence on cars, increasing fuel efficiency and the use of biofuels, making energy for homes and businesses more efficient and cleaner, building on existing policy action, and sustaining the city's commitment to reducing GHG emissions.
The first plan of action is to significantly increase the supply of frequent, reliable, and convenient public transportation.
The largest source of Seattle's GHG emissions comes from the approximately two billion miles driven by gasoline-fueled cars and trucks.
The city plans to invest $1.5 million to increase transit services.
Transit Now plans to match the $1.5 million if the ballot passes in Seattle.
Sound Transit’s Link light rail system operates between downtown Seattle and Seattle-Tacoma International Airport as an alternative to driving.
The city will implement a 10% commercial parking tax over a three-year period beginning July 2007.
Seattle plans to rezone certain areas to provide neighborhoods easy access to transits, light rail systems, and provide amenities close enough to walk or bike.
Mayor Nickels has allocated $100,000 to work with regional partners in an effort to explore and develop road pricing scenarios.
Road pricing can take the form of tolling based on road congestion, the time of day, or even miles driven.
Seattle's second plan is to increase fuel efficiency and the use of biofuels, which is projected to cut emissions by 200,600 tons.
Seattle will start by increasing the biodiesel blend from 20 percent biodiesel to as much as 40 percent in 2007.
Seattle wants to promote the use of biodiesel by making it state law to require at least 2 percent by volume of diesel sales to be biodiesel.
The port of Seattle uses B99 biodiesel for its own use and cuts emissions by turning off their diesel engines when in port by using electricity from Seattle City Light.
Seattle has a plan to encourage all city employees to reduce climate pollution not only at work but also at home.

Seattle plans to create a new Department of Executive Administration green team. This green team will assess whether to purchase climate-friendly products, such as super-efficient "80-plus" computers and servers.

Seattle's fifth plan is to inspire action through the Seattle Climate Partnership. This partnership will provide employers with resources for assessing their climate pollution and implementing strategies for reducing emissions.

The Department of Neighborhoods in Seattle will launch a Neighborhood Climate Protection Matching Fund. This fund will help promote and finance neighborhood-based projects that aim to reduce emissions and climate pollution.
As of October 2007, Seattle had exceeded their goal of reducing emissions to 8% of 1990 levels.
There are 218 cities, besides Seattle, that have joined Mayor Nickels in a campaign to reduce emissions to at least 7% of 1990 levels.
If all 219 cities meet their goal, the joint reduction of emissions would be equivalent to reductions from the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, and the Scandinavian countries combined.
Seattle is exceeding their goal of reducing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. However, population growth and resistance to alternate methods of transportation threaten their Kyoto goals.

In 1990, Seattle's greenhouse gas emissions were 8% lower than in 2005.
Despite Seattle's economic and population growth since 1990, energy use has decreased.
The Seattle Bicycle Master Plan (SBMP) aims to reduce emissions further by increasing the number of bike lanes and improving pedestrian sidewalks.
Mayor Nickels' "Center City Strategy" promotes urban and compact living in downtown Seattle and local neighborhoods.
Mayor Nickels, along with 700 other mayors nationwide, signed the US Mayors Climate Protection Agreement, which requires cities to meet or beat the Kyoto Treaty emission targets by 2012.
The state of Washington has enacted several pieces of legislation to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in areas such as construction, waste, water, and air quality.
Efforts to reduce GHG emissions must take place in Washington and globally to minimize further warming.
The legislature is searching for ways to fund the formation of renewable energy sources.
The bill SHB 1032 proposes taxing families and businesses to generate financial support for new renewable energy sources.
The bill SHB 1032 would tax every utility customer approximately $1.90 a month, regardless of how much energy the customer uses.
Industrial users would pay the same as poverty-level families under the bill SHB 1032.
The bill SHB 1032 would not provide an incentive for people to reduce their energy use.

The Climate Advisory Team (CAT) of Washington State published a guide to reducing greenhouse gases in Washington State on February 1, 2008.
The CAT's guide aims to build market-based mechanisms to encourage investment in reducing emissions.
The CAT's guide recommends establishing emissions reporting to track progress in emission reductions.
The CAT's guide suggests analyzing greenhouse gas emissions and mitigation options early in decision-making, planning processes, and development projects.
The CAT's guide proposes investing in worker training for the emerging Clean Economy.
The CAT's guide encourages building and redesigning communities to provide alternatives to single occupancy vehicles.
The CAT's guide advocates for efficient vehicles and non-carbon or lower carbon intensity fuels developed sustainably from regional resources.
The CAT's guide prioritizes moving people and goods cleanly and efficiently in transportation infrastructure investments.
The CAT's guide recommends designing, building, upgrading, and operating new and existing buildings and equipment to maximize energy efficiency.
The CAT's guide suggests delivering energy from lower or non-carbon sources and more efficient use of fuels.
The CAT's guide promotes restoring and retaining the health and vitality of Washington's farms and forest lands to increase carbon sequestration and storage in forests and forest products.
The CAT's guide encourages reducing waste and Washington's emissions of GHGs through improved product choices and resource stewardship.
The CAT's guide recommends allocating sufficient state resources to maintain Washington's leadership role regionally and nationally.
In February 2000, Seattle enacted a green building policy called the Sustainable Building Policy.
The Sustainable Building Policy requires all city-funded projects covering more than 5,000 square feet to achieve at least a LEED-silver rating.
LEED is a voluntary, national green building rating system developed by the U.S. Green Building Council.
LEED certifies buildings for their sustainable construction and operation.

Green building enhances the community and local economy.
Pollution is a global issue.
Greenhouse gas emissions continue to increase globally.
Many nations and states are taking actions to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases, including Washington state.
Washington state has teamed up with Oregon and California in an effort to reduce emissions as part of the West Coast Governors’ Global Warming Initiative.
The main greenhouse gases released in Washington include carbon dioxide (CO2), methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O), and other gases that contribute to global warming.
The different emission types are placed into three categories: energy, industrial processes and agriculture.
Different greenhouse gases range in their individual impact on global warming.
One pound of nitrous oxide is 296 times more potent than a pound of carbon dioxide in contributing to global warming.
Small quantities of gases emitted into the environment, like nitrous oxide, can have significant impacts on global warming.
In Washington state, energy-related emissions are the dominant source of GHG emissions.
Energy-related emissions in Washington state have increased from 61.2 MMT CO2-equivalent (CO2-e) in 1990 to 74.6 MMT CO2-e in 2004.
The share of energy-related emissions in Washington state has increased from 79% of total emissions to 85% over the past fourteen years.
Carbon dioxide is the dominant GHG in Washington state, followed by methane, nitrous oxide, perfluorocarbon and sulfur hexafluoride (SF6).
Non-energy industrial global greenhouse gas emissions in Washington state have lowered from 14% to 9%.
The reduction in non-energy industrial global greenhouse gas emissions in Washington state is mainly due to reduced emissions from aluminum production.
